{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479096"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:20:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:20:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19194"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19194"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.03,0.07,0.62,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81964"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11928"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19194"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67229"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"339"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44972"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81964"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of right-sided facial swelling and fever. His parent reports he has been drinking less than usual and is more irritable. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date, including mumps vaccination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. There is a tender, warm, erythematous swelling over his right parotid gland. Gentle pressure on the parotid gland expresses purulent material from Stensen\u0027s duct.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral amoxicillin","Observation only","Oral paracetamol only","Intravenous flucloxacillin","Mumps immunoglobulin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with acute bacterial parotitis, characterised by unilateral parotid swelling, fever, and purulent discharge from Stensen\u0027s duct. The most common causative organism is \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E, which typically ascends through Stensen\u0027s duct. Risk factors include dehydration, poor oral intake, and immunosuppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial treatment as it provides excellent coverage against \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E. The presence of systemic symptoms and young age warrant intravenous rather than oral therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E would provide inadequate coverage against \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and would be inappropriate given the severity of symptoms and likely dehydration affecting oral absorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral paracetamol\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient as antimicrobial therapy is required to treat the underlying bacterial infection. While antipyretics are helpful for symptom control, they should not be the only treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMumps immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as this is not a case of mumps. The acute onset, unilateral involvement, and presence of purulent discharge are more consistent with bacterial parotitis. Additionally, the child is already immunised against mumps.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation only\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the presence of fever, systemic symptoms, and evidence of bacterial infection. Delayed treatment could lead to complications such as abscess formation or sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional management should include adequate hydration, analgesia, and encouragement of oral intake and parotid gland massage once the acute phase has settled to prevent stasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute bacterial parotitis in children is most commonly caused by Staphylococcus aureus ascending through Stensen\u0027s duct.","Dehydration and poor oral intake are significant risk factors for bacterial parotitis in children.","First-line treatment for bacterial parotitis is intravenous flucloxacillin to cover Staphylococcus aureus."],"references":["Kliegman RM, St. Geme JW, Blum NJ, Shah SS, Tasker RC, Wilson KM, editors. Parotitis. In: Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics. 21st ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67229"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19194"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67229"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T13:47:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T13:49:3